
# 📊 Splunk SPL Cheatsheet

SPL (Search Processing Language) is the query language used in Splunk to search, filter, and analyse log data. This cheatsheet covers everything needed for the 9 lab projects.

---

## 🔎 Basic Search Syntax

```spl
index=lab_logs                          ← Search all logs in lab_logs index
index=lab_logs sourcetype=syslog        ← Filter by source type
index=lab_logs "Failed password"        ← Search for keyword
index=lab_logs host=metasploitable      ← Filter by hostname
index=lab_logs src_ip=192.168.248.3     ← Filter by source IP
index=* earliest=-24h latest=now        ← Last 24 hours across all indexes
```

---

## 🔑 Essential SPL Commands

| Command | What It Does | Example |
|---------|-------------|---------|
| `search` | Filter events | `search "Failed password"` |
| `fields` | Keep or remove fields | `fields src_ip, user, action` |
| `table` | Display results as table | `table _time, src_ip, user` |
| `stats` | Calculate statistics | `stats count by src_ip` |
| `sort` | Sort results | `sort -count` |
| `head` | Show first N results | `head 10` |
| `tail` | Show last N results | `tail 10` |
| `dedup` | Remove duplicates | `dedup src_ip` |
| `rename` | Rename a field | `rename src_ip as "Source IP"` |
| `eval` | Create calculated field | `eval risk=count*10` |
| `rex` | Extract fields with regex | `rex field=_raw "user=(?<username>\w+)"` |
| `timechart` | Chart over time | `timechart count by src_ip` |
| `chart` | Create charts | `chart count by user` |
| `where` | Filter with conditions | `where count > 5` |
| `join` | Join two searches | `join src_ip [search index=blocklist]` |

